[[File:Gene kelly.jpg|thumb|alt=A photograph of Gene Kelly.|Kelly in 1943]]
[[Gene Kelly]] (1912–1996) was an American [[dance]]r, [[actor]], [[singing|singer]], [[film director|director]], [[Film producer|producer]] and [[choreographer]] whose work in [[film|motion pictures]] spans from 1942 to 1996. He is probably best known today for his performances in musicals, notably ''[[An American in Paris (film)|An American in Paris]]'' (1951) and ''[[Singin' in the Rain]]'' (1952).

Kelly made his [[Hollywood]] film debut in ''[[For Me and My Gal (film)|For Me and My Gal]]'' (1942), co-starring with [[Judy Garland]].<ref name="PBS-Masters">{{cite web| url = https://www.pbs.org/wnet/americanmasters/episodes/gene-kelly/anatomy-of-a-dancer/516/| title = Gene Kelly&nbsp;— Anatomy of a Dancer| work = [[American Masters]]| publisher = [[Public Broadcasting Service]]| accessdate = 2009-03-03}}</ref> Afterward, he went on to work as an actor, dancer and subsequently, choreographer, in a series of musical films. In these films, his choreography included experiments with a combination of dance and animation (''[[Anchors Aweigh (film)|Anchors Aweigh]]'' and ''[[Invitation to the Dance (film)|Invitation to the Dance]]'') and dance scenes involving special effects (including the "Alter Ego" number from ''[[Cover Girl (film)|Cover Girl]]'' and the split-screen dance number from ''[[It's Always Fair Weather]]'').{{sfn|Thomas|1991|p=52}}{{sfn|Thomas|1991|p=162}} In addition to his work as an actor and choreographer, Kelly directed or co-directed several films, some of which did not feature him in an acting role. Kelly appeared in several non-musical [[drama]]tic and [[comedy]] films as well.

Kelly received an [[Academy Award]] nomination for [[Academy Award for Best Actor|Best Actor]] for his performance in ''Anchors Aweigh'' (1945) and won an [[Academy Honorary Award#1950s|Honorary Academy Award]] for his work in ''An American in Paris'' (1951).<ref>{{cite web| url = http://awardsdatabase.oscars.org/ampas_awards/DisplayMain.jsp;jsessionid=67816743B3229B413ADF31E8376268AE.squash?curTime=1237320849022| title = Gene Kelly: Awards| publisher = Academy of Motion Picture Arts and Sciences| accessdate = 2009-03-17| quote = In appreciation of his versatility as an actor, singer, director and dancer, and specifically for his brilliant achievements in the art of choreography on film.}}{{dead link|date=September 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> He was voted the 15th most popular film actor on the [[American Film Institute]]’s millennium list, while his ''Singin' in the Rain'' was voted the [[AFI's 100 Years of Musicals|most popular movie musical of all time]].<ref name="PBS-Masters" /><ref>{{cite web| url = http://www.afi.com/100years/musicals.aspx| title = AFI's Greatest Movie Musicals| publisher = [[American Film Institute]]| year = 2010| accessdate = 2010-10-14}}</ref>
This filmography below contains a chronological listing of Gene Kelly's feature films. His musicals are indicated with a beamed [[eighth note]] symbol (♫).

