{{DEFAULTSORT:Northrop, James Henry}} [[Category:Weavers]] [[Category:People of the Industrial Revolution]] [[Category:English inventors]] [[Category:Textile workers]] [[Category:People from Keighley]] [[Category:1856 births]] [[Category:1940 deaths]]

{{Infobox person | name = John Page Hopps | image = John Page Hopps.png |birth_date = 6 November 1834 |death_date = {{dda|1911|4|6|1834|11|6|df=y}} | occupation = [[Unitarianism|Unitarian]] minister, spiritualist }}
'''John Page Hopps''' (6 November 1834 - 6 April 1911) was a [[Unitarianism|Unitarian]] minister and [[Spiritualism|spiritualist]].<ref name="Watts">Watts, Michael R. (2015). ''The Dissenters: Volume III: The Crisis and Conscience of Nonconformity''. Oxford University Press. pp. 37-38. {{ISBN|978-0198229698}}</ref><ref>John Page Hopps. [https://hymnology.hymnsam.co.uk/j/john-page-hopps ''The Canterbury Dictionary of Hymnology'']. Canterbury Press, accessed December 3, 2016.</ref>
Hopps was born in [[London]]. He was educated at the General Baptist College, [[Leicester]]. He worked as [[George Dawson (preacher)|George Dawson]]'s assistant at the [[Church of the Saviour, Birmingham]] and from 1860 to 1876 he ministered to Unitarians.<ref>[http://www.hymnary.org/person/Hopps_JP "John Page Hopps"]. Hymnary.</ref> He was a minister at the Unitarian Church in Bath Street, [[Glasgow]].<ref>[http://www.theglasgowstory.com/image/?inum=TGSA00023 "John Page Hopps"]. The Glasgow Story.</ref> Hopps was a convinced spiritualist and was influenced by [[William Howitt]] and [[C. F. Varley]]. He had unified his unitarianism with spiritualism by arguing the [[bible]] was a record of spirit communication.<ref name="Watts"/>
In a lecture for the [[London Spiritualist Alliance]], Hopps supported biological [[evolution]] and spiritualism.<ref>Oppenheim, Janet. (1988). ''The Other World: Spiritualism and Psychical Research in England, 1850–1914''. Cambridge University Press. p. 270. {{ISBN|978-0521347679}}</ref>
He created and edited the monthly periodical ''The Truthseeker'' (1863-1887).<ref>[http://www.cyberhymnal.org/bio/h/o/p/hopps_jp.htm "John Page Hopps"]. NetHymnal.</ref> Hopps also edited a spiritualist newspaper ''Daybreak'', which was absorbed into the weekly spiritualist newspaper ''The Medium and Daybreak'' of [[James Burns (Spiritualist)|James Burns]].<ref>Oppenheim, Janet. (1988). ''The Other World: Spiritualism and Psychical Research in England, 1850–1914''. Cambridge University Press. p. 45. {{ISBN|978-0521347679}}</ref><ref>Lavoie, Jeffrey D. (2012). ''The Theosophical Society: The History of a Spiritualist Movement''. BrownWalker Press. p. 152. {{ISBN|978-1612335537}}</ref> In 1886 his "Letter to a Radical Member of Parliament" advocating women's suffrage was published in the Manchester-based ''[[Women's Suffrage Journal]]''. In it he wrote, "I do not believe that women would hinder progress. I think that as [to] questions relating to peace and war, social purity, and the doing of equal justice to all, they would help us on. But if the reverse were the case, what right have we to deny them the suffrage for ''that'' reason? Who is the infallible judge as to what 'progress' is, and who gave that judge the right to have ''his'' way?"<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Hopps|first=J. Page|date=1 November 1886|title=A Letter to a Radical Member of Parliament|url=http://gdc.galegroup.com.ezproxy.gc.cuny.edu/gdc/ncco/NewspapersDetailsPage/NewspapersDetailsWindow?disableHighlighting=false&displayGroupName=DVI-Newspapers&docIndex=28&source=fullList&prodId=NCCO&mode=view&limiter=&display-query=TX+equal+AND+PU+%22Women%27s+Suffrage+Journal%22&contentModules=&action=e&sortBy=&windowstate=normal&currPage=6&dviSelectedPage=&scanId=&query=TX+equal+AND+PU+%22Women%27s+Suffrage+Journal%22&search_within_results=&p=NCCO&catId=&u=cuny_gradctr&displayGroups=DVI-Newspapers&documentId=GALE%7CKKYFJR643478995&activityType=BasicSearch&failOverType=&commentary=|journal=Women's Suffrage Journal|volume=XVII|pages=153|via=Nineteenth Century Collections Online}}</ref>
