{{Infobox artist | name = Mary Georgina Filmer | image = | imagesize = | caption = | birth_name = Mary Georgina Caroline Cecil | birth_date = {{birth date|1838|4|4|mf=y}} | birth_place = | death_date = {{death date and age|1903|3|17|1838|4|4|mf=y}} | death_place = London, United Kingdom | nationality = [[United Kingdom|British]] | education = | field = [[Photomontage]] | training = | movement = | works = | patrons = | awards = | spouse = Edmund Filmer }}
[[File:Mary-georgiana-caroline-lady-filmer-untitled-loose-page-from-the-filmer-album-mid-1860s.jpg|thumb|Collage by Mary Georgina Filmer (mid-1860s)]] Lady '''Mary Georgina Filmer''' (née Cecil, 4 April 1838 &ndash; 17 March 1903) was an early proponent of the art of photographic [[collage]].<ref>[http://www.luminous-lint.com/app/photographer/Lady_Mary_Georgiana__Filmer/A/ "Lady Mary Georgiana Filmer"], Luminous Lint. Retrieved 13 March 2013.</ref><ref>[http://www.kevyoung.com/familytree_files/f_150.html#4 "CECIL, Mary Georgina Caroline"]. Retrieved 13 March 2013.</ref>
A [[Victorian era|Victorian]] socialite, Lady Filmer produced several albums consisting of watercolour scenes decorated with [[photomontage]]s.<ref>[http://www.musee-orsay.fr/en/collections/works-in-focus/photography/commentaire_id/photomontage-15690.html?tx_commentaire_pi1%5BpidLi%5D=847&tx_commentaire_pi1%5Bfrom%5D=844&cHash=d1d5de53d5 "Lady Filmer: Photomontage"], Musée d'Orsay. Retrieved 13 March 2013.</ref> One of her works (from the so-called ''Filmer Album'') depicts a drawing room, painted in watercolour, in which she has added photographic cut-outs from [[albumen silver print]]s. She positions herself next to a large figure of the [[Edward VII|Prince of Wales]], with whom she was known to flirt.<ref>[http://art.newcity.com/2009/10/12/review-playing-with-picturesart-institute-of-chicago/ Claudine Isé, "Review: Playing with Pictures/Art Institute of Chicago"], Newcity Art. Retrieved 13 March 2013.</ref> Her albums and glue pot are set out on a large table beside her. Much smaller, [[Sir Edmund Filmer, 9th Baronet|Sir Edmund Filmer]], her husband, is seated next to a pet dog. In 2010, the work was included in an exhibition at the [[Metropolitan Museum of Art]] titled "Playing With Pictures: The Art of Victorian Photocollage".<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/2010/02/05/arts/design/05victorian.html Roberta Smith, "The Pastime of Victorian Cutups"], ''The New York Times'', 4 February 2010. Retrieved 13 March 2013.</ref>
